    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí## Intro<a name="intro"></a>
    34‚ÜíTomli is a Python library for parsing [TOML](https://toml.io).
    35‚ÜíVersion 2.4.0 and later are compatible with [TOML v1.1.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.1.0).
    36‚ÜíOlder versions are [TOML v1.0.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.0.0) compatible.
    37‚Üí
    38‚ÜíA version of Tomli, the `tomllib` module,
    39‚Üíwas added to the standard library in Python 3.11
    40‚Üívia [PEP 680](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0680/).
    41‚ÜíTomli continues to provide a backport on PyPI for Python versions
    42‚Üíwhere the standard library module is not available
    43‚Üíand that have not yet reached their end-of-life.
    44‚Üí
    45‚ÜíTomli uses [mypyc](https://github.com/mypyc/mypyc)
    46‚Üíto generate binary wheels for most of the widely used platforms,
    47‚Üíso Python 3.11+ users may prefer it over `tomllib` for improved performance.
    48‚ÜíPure Python wheels are available on any platform and should perform the same as `tomllib`.
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí## Installation<a name="installation"></a>
    52‚Üí```bash
    53‚Üípip install tomli
    54‚Üí```
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí## Usage<a name="usage"></a>
    58‚Üí### Parse a TOML string<a name="parse-a-toml-string"></a>
    60‚Üí```python
    61‚Üíimport tomli
    62‚Üí
    63‚Üítoml_str = """
    64‚Üí[[players]]
    65‚Üíname = "Lehtinen"
    66‚Üínumber = 26
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí[[players]]
    69‚Üíname = "Numminen"
    70‚Üínumber = 27
    71‚Üí"""
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üítoml_dict = tomli.loads(toml_str)
    74‚Üíassert toml_dict == {
    75‚Üí    "players": [{"name": "Lehtinen", "number": 26}, {"name": "Numminen", "number": 27}]
    76‚Üí}
    77‚Üí```
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí### Parse a TOML file<a name="parse-a-toml-file"></a>
    81‚Üí```python
    82‚Üíimport tomli
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üíwith open("path_to_file/conf.toml", "rb") as f:
    85‚Üí    toml_dict = tomli.load(f)
    86‚Üí```
    87‚Üí
    88‚ÜíThe file must be opened in binary mode (with the `"rb"` flag).
    89‚ÜíBinary mode will enforce decoding the file as UTF-8 with universal newlines disabled,
    90‚Üíboth of which are required to correctly parse TOML.
    91‚Üí
    92‚Üí### Handle invalid TOML<a name="handle-invalid-toml"></a>
    94‚Üí```python
    95‚Üíimport tomli
    96‚Üí
    97‚Üítry:
    98‚Üí    toml_dict = tomli.loads("]] this is invalid TOML [[")
    99‚Üíexcept tomli.TOMLDecodeError:
   100‚Üí    print("Yep, definitely not valid.")
   101‚Üí```
   102‚Üí
   103‚ÜíNote that error messages are considered informational only.
   104‚ÜíThey should not be assumed to stay constant across Tomli versions.
   105‚Üí
   106‚Üí### Construct `decimal.Decimal`s from TOML floats<a name="construct-decimaldecimals-from-toml-floats"></a>
   108‚Üí```python
   109‚Üífrom decimal import Decimal
   110‚Üíimport tomli
   111‚Üí
   112‚Üítoml_dict = tomli.loads("precision-matters = 0.982492", parse_float=Decimal)
   113‚Üíassert isinstance(toml_dict["precision-matters"], Decimal)
   114‚Üíassert toml_dict["precision-matters"] == Decimal("0.982492")
   115‚Üí```
   116‚Üí
   117‚ÜíNote that `decimal.Decimal` can be replaced with another callable that converts a TOML float from string to a Python type.
   118‚ÜíThe `decimal.Decimal` is, however, a practical choice for use cases where float inaccuracies can not be tolerated.
   119‚Üí
   120‚ÜíIllegal types are `dict` and `list`, and their subtypes.
   121‚ÜíA `ValueError` will be raised if `parse_float` produces illegal types.
   122‚Üí
   123‚Üí### Building a `tomli`/`tomllib` compatibility layer<a name="building-a-tomlitomllib-compatibility-layer"></a>
   125‚ÜíPython versions 3.11+ ship with a version of Tomli:
   126‚Üíthe `tomllib` standard library module.
   127‚ÜíTo build code that uses the standard library if available,
   128‚Üíbut still works seamlessly with Python 3.6+,
   129‚Üído the following.
   130‚Üí
   131‚ÜíInstead of a hard Tomli dependency, use the following
   132‚Üí[dependency specifier](https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/specifications/dependency-specifiers/)
   133‚Üíto only require Tomli when the standard library module is not available:
   134‚Üí
   135‚Üí```
   136‚Üítomli >= 1.1.0 ; python_version < "3.11"
   137‚Üí```
   138‚Üí
   139‚ÜíThen, in your code, import a TOML parser using the following fallback mechanism:
   140‚Üí
   141‚Üí```python
   142‚Üíimport sys
   143‚Üí
   144‚Üíif sys.version_info >= (3, 11):
   145‚Üí    import tomllib
   146‚Üíelse:
   147‚Üí    import tomli as tomllib
   148‚Üí
   149‚Üítomllib.loads("['This parses fine with Python 3.6+']")
   150‚Üí```
   151‚Üí
   152‚Üí## FAQ<a name="faq"></a>
   154‚Üí### Why this parser?<a name="why-this-parser"></a>
   156‚Üí- it's lil'
   157‚Üí- pure Python with zero dependencies
   158‚Üí- the fastest pure Python parser [\*](#pure-python):
   159‚Üí  14x as fast as [tomlkit](https://pypi.org/project/tomlkit/),
   160‚Üí  2.1x as fast as [toml](https://pypi.org/project/toml/)
   161‚Üí- outputs [basic data types](#how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types) only
   162‚Üí- 100% spec compliant: passes all tests in
   163‚Üí  [toml-lang/toml-test](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml-test)
   164‚Üí  test suite
   165‚Üí- thoroughly tested: 100% branch coverage
   166‚Üí
   167‚Üí### Is comment preserving round-trip parsing supported?<a name="is-comment-preserving-round-trip-parsing-supported"></a>
   169‚ÜíNo.
   170‚Üí
   171‚ÜíThe `tomli.loads` function returns a plain `dict` that is populated with builtin types and types from the standard library only.
   172‚ÜíPreserving comments requires a custom type to be returned so will not be supported,
   173‚Üíat least not by the `tomli.loads` and `tomli.load` functions.
   174‚Üí
   175‚ÜíLook into [TOML Kit](https://github.com/sdispater/tomlkit) if preservation of style is what you need.
   176‚Üí
   177‚Üí### Is there a `dumps`, `write` or `encode` function?<a name="is-there-a-dumps-write-or-encode-function"></a>
   179‚Üí[Tomli-W](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli-w) is the write-only counterpart of Tomli, providing `dump` and `dumps` functions.
   180‚Üí
   181‚ÜíThe core library does not include write capability, as most TOML use cases are read-only, and Tomli intends to be minimal.
   182‚Üí
   183‚Üí### How do TOML types map into Python types?<a name="how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types"></a>
   185‚Üí| TOML type        | Python type         | Details                                                      |
   186‚Üí| ---------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
   187‚Üí| Document Root    | `dict`              |                                                              |
   188‚Üí| Key              | `str`               |                                                              |
   189‚Üí| String           | `str`               |                                                              |
   190‚Üí| Integer          | `int`               |                                                              |
   191‚Üí| Float            | `float`             |                                                              |
   192‚Üí| Boolean          | `bool`              |                                                              |
   193‚Üí| Offset Date-Time | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to an instance of `datetime.timezone` |
   194‚Üí| Local Date-Time  | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to `None`                             |
   195‚Üí| Local Date       | `datetime.date`     |                                                              |
   196‚Üí| Local Time       | `datetime.time`     |                                                              |
   197‚Üí| Array            | `list`              |                                                              |
   198‚Üí| Table            | `dict`              |                                                              |
   199‚Üí| Inline Table     | `dict`              |                                                              |
   200‚Üí
   201‚Üí## Performance<a name="performance"></a>
   203‚ÜíThe `benchmark/` folder in this repository contains a performance benchmark for comparing the various Python TOML parsers.
   204‚Üí
   205‚ÜíBelow are the results for commit [064e492](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli/tree/064e492919b2338def788753b8c981c9131334c0).
   206‚Üí
   207‚Üí### Mypyc generated wheel<a name="mypyc-generated-wheel"></a>
   209‚Üí```console
   210‚Üífoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python --version
   211‚ÜíPython 3.14.2
   212‚Üífoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ pip freeze
   213‚Üípytomlpp==1.1.0
   214‚Üírtoml==0.13.0
   215‚Üítoml==0.10.2
   216‚Üítomli @ file:///home/foo/dev/tomli
   217‚Üítomlkit==0.13.3
   218‚Üífoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   219‚ÜíParsing data.toml 5000 times:
   220‚Üí------------------------------------------------------
   221‚Üí    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   222‚Üí-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   223‚Üí     rtoml |    0.328 s | baseline (100%)
   224‚Üí  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 89.75%
   225‚Üí     tomli |    0.838 s | 39.12%
   226‚Üí      toml |     3.01 s | 10.90%
   227‚Üí   tomlkit |     20.7 s | 1.59%
   228‚Üí```
   229‚Üí
   230‚Üí### Pure Python<a name="pure-python"></a>
   232‚Üí```console
   233‚Üífoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   234‚ÜíParsing data.toml 5000 times:
   235‚Üí------------------------------------------------------
   236‚Üí    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   237‚Üí-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   238‚Üí     rtoml |    0.323 s | baseline (100%)
   239‚Üí  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 88.40%
   240‚Üí     tomli |     1.44 s | 22.36%
   241‚Üí      toml |     3.03 s | 10.65%
   242‚Üí   tomlkit |     20.6 s | 1.57%
   243‚Üí```
fuzzer/fuzz.py
    20‚Üídef test_one_input(input_bytes: bytes) -> None:
    21‚Üí    # We need a Unicode string, not bytes
    22‚Üí    fdp = atheris.FuzzedDataProvider(input_bytes)
    23‚Üí    data = fdp.ConsumeUnicode(sys.maxsize)
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí    try:
    26‚Üí        toml_obj = tomli.loads(data)
    27‚Üí    except (tomli.TOMLDecodeError, RecursionError):
    28‚Üí        return
    29‚Üí    except BaseException:
    30‚Üí        print_err(data)
    31‚Üí        raise
    32‚Üí
    33‚Üí    try:
    34‚Üí        recovered_data = tomli_w.dumps(toml_obj)
    35‚Üí    except RecursionError:
    36‚Üí        return
    37‚Üí    except BaseException:
    38‚Üí        print_err(data)
    39‚Üí        raise
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí    roundtripped_obj = tomli.loads(recovered_data)
    42‚Üí    normalize_toml_obj(roundtripped_obj)
    43‚Üí    normalize_toml_obj(toml_obj)
    44‚Üí    if roundtripped_obj != toml_obj:
    45‚Üí        sys.stderr.write(
    46‚Üí            f"Original dict:\n{toml_obj}\nRoundtripped dict:\n{roundtripped_obj}\n"
    47‚Üí        )
    48‚Üí        sys.stderr.flush()
    49‚Üí        print_err(data)
    50‚Üí        raise Exception("Dicts not equal after roundtrip")
    53‚Üídef print_err(data):
    54‚Üí    codepoints = [hex(ord(x)) for x in data]
    55‚Üí    sys.stderr.write(f"Input was {type(data)}:\n{data}\nCodepoints:\n{codepoints}\n")
    56‚Üí    sys.stderr.flush()
    59‚Üídef normalize_toml_obj(toml_obj: dict) -> None:
    60‚Üí    """Make NaNs equal when compared (without using recursion)."""
    61‚Üí    to_process = [toml_obj]
    62‚Üí    while to_process:
    63‚Üí        cont = to_process.pop()
    64‚Üí        for k, v in cont.items() if isinstance(cont, dict) else enumerate(cont):
    65‚Üí            if isinstance(v, float) and isnan(v):
    66‚Üí                cont[k] = "nan"
    67‚Üí            elif isinstance(v, (dict, list)):
    68‚Üí                to_process.append(v)
    71‚Üídef main():
    72‚Üí    # For possible options, see https://llvm.org/docs/LibFuzzer.html#options
    73‚Üí    fuzzer_options = sys.argv
    74‚Üí    atheris.Setup(fuzzer_options, test_one_input)
    75‚Üí    atheris.Fuzz()
scripts/use_setuptools.py
    12‚Üídef use_setuptools() -> None:
    13‚Üí    pyproject_path = Path(__file__).parent.parent / "pyproject.toml"
    14‚Üí    data = tomllib.loads(pyproject_path.read_bytes().decode())
    15‚Üí    data["build-system"] = {
    16‚Üí        "requires": ["setuptools>=77.0.3", "mypy[mypyc]>=1.15"],
    17‚Üí        "build-backend": "setuptools.build_meta",
    18‚Üí    }
    19‚Üí    pyproject_path.write_bytes(tomli_w.dumps(data).encode())
